    "description": "Inverted cone-shaped body with wide-rimmed circular mouth and cross-form base; two vertical tubular handles with flat horizontal mounts at rim and lower body.",
    "justification": "After&amp;nbsp;studying in Budapest, Ilonka Karasz arrived&amp;nbsp;in the United States in 1913, where&amp;nbsp;a little over ten&amp;nbsp;years later&amp;nbsp;she began to establish herself as an influential designer in&amp;nbsp;a variety of media. Although her designs show multiple references to her European past, they also display a combination of unique ideas associated with her new home. In this silver-plated sugar bowl and creamer, she developed the idea of using one form and adapting it with additional elements and parts. These cone-shaped metal forms are modified with the inclusion of four triangular planes&amp;nbsp;to form&amp;nbsp;stable cross-shaped bases. In fact, early in her career, Karasz tried to create objects featuring various planar surfaces. The use of silver-plated nickel,&amp;nbsp;instead of expensive solid silver,and&amp;nbsp;the pure geometric shapes that&amp;nbsp;imply industrial production make these serving pieces&amp;nbsp;easy to clean and&amp;nbsp;maintain&amp;nbsp;and present an aesthetic&amp;nbsp;suitable for any modern&amp;nbsp;interior.&amp;nbsp; The forms&amp;nbsp;also&amp;nbsp;suggest&amp;nbsp;Karasz's democratic vision of the United States as American society entered&amp;nbsp;the modern&amp;nbsp;age.",
